Trading opportunistically @realmoney As is customary I trade around my positions - especially those of an Index kind. The S&P just dropped by 40 handles and the Nasdaq by over 100 points - somewhat moderating the trade calculus of these shorts.
I just moved from large to medium sized in SPY and QQQ, covering at $287.55 and $183.90, respectively. I will move back to large sized on a rally - if it occurs over the near term.
This brings me back to between small and medium sized net short of exposure. @jimcramer @tomkeene

Memo to biz media commentators. Before asking rate or market forecasts - find out what the views were twelve months ago. How else can viewers distinguish good from bad input? I make plenty of mistakes and I own up to them. @dwyerstrategy @fundstrat are two examples of guys who
fully admit their investment boners. There are few others that are genuine.

A documented history of successful returns or investment recommendations has never been a reason to book or mention a view in the biz financial media. Its unsettling but true. There are too many merchants of attention, sellers of a service and not bonafide practitioners.

Some midday comments and observations: 1. If the bond market isn't scaring you as an equity investor you are a blind man. 2. There is nothing like price to change sentiment. The boys will now be bullish (and they sold the top).

3. UBS is now predicting 1.25% ten year note yield. (A year ago they were predicting 3.1%). Res ipsa loquitor. 4. $GLD and $VXX are today's standout winners. 5. 4-1 negative breadth. 6. "Peak Trump"- his election odds will now begin a descent. Not even Harvey Spector could save
the S&P. en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suits_…

No, I don't disagree with your observation. I do disagree that sentiment or views are gloomy and delivered at a shrill level. By no means is it. I don't know a balanced strategist/talking head who sees a large mkt drawdown. I still see complacency.
@revshark Rev I have always found "sentiment' as a loose indicator as we can always find a sentiment indicator that is bullish or bearish. As to brokerage views, a thin reed indicator.
challenge.
My twitter thread is bunched up with somewhat hyperbolic observations that the market gloom and doom is palpable. I see much more complacency compared to calls of disaster. -

Even my @realmoney comments are measured and not gloom like. I see an impt top in Jan 2018, much more volatility and a lower market but no disaster.... Could it turn into something worse? Yes it could. Stay tuned.

I am not arguing with your statement just tweeted but I am disagreeing with the characterization of the brokerage forecasts being a "disaster." And the "shrill" designation. I see few legit sources calling for a meaningful mkt drawdown. Those are my (respectful) points.

You tweeted that bears are increasingly confident and predictions of disaster are becoming shrill. I don't see $MS $GS or $JPM mkt forecasts as a prediction of disaster based on their specific S&P price targets.

Rev, if you can show me increasingly confident disaster calls from previously objective talking heads I would take under advisement but I don't see this from anyone save perma Bears. But I am willing to adjust my thinking if you can show me evidence. Rather, I see complacency &
little talk of a possible large mkt drawdown.
